                <tr><td>Tokenization fee (at CCT mint)</td><td>40 bps of bar value</td><td>50% vault / 50% OpCo</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Collateralization fee (at SMU mint)</td><td>20 bps</td><td>50% vault / 50% OpCo</td></tr>
                <tr><td>gGold mint/burn — frontend</td><td>10 bps</td><td>OpCo</td></tr>
                <tr><td>gGold mint/burn — protocol</td><td>12.5 bps</td><td>Protocol treasury</td></tr>
                <tr><td>DEX routing — frontend</td><td>.25 bps of routed volume</td><td>OpCo</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Marketplace take (Year 2+)</td><td>75 bps</td><td>OpCo</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Perpetuals trading (Year 3+, Series A funded)</td><td>2.5 bps</td><td>OpCo</td></tr>
                <tr><td>KYC verification rails</td><td>30% of $75/verification</td><td>OpCo</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Title Register</td><td><strong>Free, forever</strong></td><td>— (the wedge)</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p>Three design choices matter to an investor:</p>
          <ul class="memo-list">
            <li>
              <strong>The Title Register is free forever.</strong> It is the door
              through which every vault enters the network — deliberately
              unmonetized, the way the best infrastructure wedges always are.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The vault earns more as a node than as a warehouse.</strong>
              A vault's legacy business earns ~0.2%/yr on stored AUM. As a network
              node — earning tokenization shares, collateralization shares,
              title-transfer fees, KYC fees, and storage on non-collateralized
              bars — the model shows vaults earning <strong>1.3–3.5x their legacy
              storage revenue</strong>, with an automated floor check that
              guarantees the pitch never inverts. That is the sales conversation:
              not "adopt our software," but "upgrade your business model."
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>No rented TVL in the model.</strong> Every dollar of modeled
              revenue is a fee on a real action against real metal —
              tokenization, collateralization, routing, verification, marketplace
              activity, and trading. The business case does not depend on
              subsidized liquidity or emissions-driven growth.
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong>Go-to-market.</strong> Launch with the Wyoming Reserve at
            platform go-live (month 4); 3 vaults by end of Year 1, 10 by end of
            Year 2, 40 by Year 5 — driven by two BD leads (gold industry and
            Web3), a two-sided referral engine (25% of later vaults arrive by
            referral, at half the acquisition cost), and Foundation grants funding
            DeFi integrations. Vault CAC runs ~$50k against OpCo revenue per vault
            of ~$340–385k in the first two years: <strong>roughly two-month CAC
            payback and a 26x LTV/CAC ratio.</strong>
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- 6 · FINANCIAL PLAN -->
        <section id="financial-plan" class="memo-section" data-memo-section>
          <h2 class="display display--md">IV. The Financial Plan</h2>
          <p>
            The full model is a 21-tab institutional workbook — a monthly engine
            across 60 months, three scenarios, and 26 automated integrity checks,
            all passing in every scenario. Its central discipline: <strong>TVL is
            an output.</strong> Demand from five modeled customer segments meets
            vault capacity through MIN(demand, supply) each month; bars enter
            custody only when there is demand for them; unmet demand queues as
            backlog. Nothing is asserted top-down.
          </p>
          <p>
