              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>Gold — LP treasury (6 gold/gold pools)</td><td>$2,000,000</td><td>40%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Team &amp; payroll (loaded)</td><td>$1,159,000</td><td>23%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Entity setup, audits &amp; attestations</td><td>$622,000</td><td>12%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Marketing, BD &amp; vault acquisition</td><td>$447,000</td><td>9%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Legal &amp; regulatory</td><td>$333,000</td><td>7%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Tech, G&amp;A, insurance</td><td>$291,000</td><td>6%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Contingency</td><td>$148,000</td><td>3%</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Total</strong></td><td><strong>$5,000,000</strong></td><td><strong>100%</strong></td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p>
            Founders take $20k/month each; the CTO $120k/year — below-market and
            equity-aligned. Operating revenue earned before the Series A (~$2.5M
            modeled) funds the balance of the pre-A plan. No bridge required in
            any scenario.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- 7 · GOLD POSITION -->
        <section id="gold-position" class="memo-section" data-memo-section>
          <h2 class="display display--md">V. The Gold Position — Why 40% of This Round Is De-Risked</h2>
          <p>
            The $2M treasury deployment is not working capital. It is a gold
            position with three jobs:
          </p>
          <ol class="memo-list memo-list--numbered">
            <li>
              <strong>Gold appreciation.</strong> $2M marked on the modeled gold
              path reaches ~$4.3M by Year 5 — the "you believe gold goes up"
              payoff, aligned with the thesis that brought investors to the memo.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Fee income.</strong> The pools earn trading fees, recycled
              and compounding — ~$0.8M more by Year 5.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Runway insurance.</strong> A needs-based drawdown policy —
              contractual, under the term sheet's Treasury Policy covenant — tops
              up operating cash automatically if the Series A slips. In the Bear
              case it bridges the company to a late A; in the Base case it is
              never touched.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            Idle operating cash above working-capital needs sweeps into the same
            instruments. Operating risk is confined to roughly $3M of the round —
            and on the Base gold path, the treasury alone returns approximately
            the entire operating budget.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- 8 · RETURNS -->
        <section id="returns" class="memo-section" data-memo-section>
          <h2 class="display display--md">VI. Returns Analysis</h2>
          <p>
            Applying protocol/infrastructure multiples (10–20x revenue; 15–30x
            EBITDA) to Year-5 Base financials implies a valuation of
            <strong>$1.6B–$3.7B (mid: ~$3.1B)</strong>. After post-Series-A
            dilution and an ESOP refresh, seed ownership at exit is ~8.3%:
          </p>
          <div class="memo-table-wrap">
            <table class="memo-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="col">Exit value</th>
                  <th scope="col">Seed proceeds</th>
                  <th scope="col">Seed MOIC</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>$250M</td><td>$21M</td><td>4.1x</td></tr>
                <tr><td>$500M</td><td>$41M</td><td>8.3x</td></tr>
                <tr><td>$1.0B</td><td>$83M</td><td>16.6x</td></tr>
                <tr><td>$2.0B</td><td>$166M</td><td>33.1x</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Base-case implied (~$3.1B)</td><td>~$255M</td><td><strong>~51x</strong></td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p>
            The 1x non-participating preference protects the legal floor; the Bear
            case protects it operationally at ~2.9x. The Series A is planned at
            $18M on $90–120M post — a 2.1x step-up, priced so the A investor
            underwrites observable month-15 milestones rather than this model.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- 9 · MOAT -->
        <section id="moat" class="memo-section" data-memo-section>
          <h2 class="display display--md">VII. The Moat</h2>
          <p>Three legs. Each alone is replicable. Together, they are not.</p>
          <ol class="memo-list memo-list--numbered">
            <li>
              <strong>Legal architecture.</strong> The CCT is a per-bar claim
              instrument that is not title, not a warehouse receipt, and not a
              security — patent pending. It creates a two-layer separation of the
              title instrument from the settlement instrument, each with its own
              classification. Counsel of record: Paul Hastings, LLP.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Distribution lock.</strong> Every vault that deploys a Title
              Register is a vault a competitor cannot easily reach — the register
              is the vault's own book of record, free forever, woven into its
              operations. The network compounds: each onboarded vault makes the
              next more valuable, and 25% of later vaults arrive by referral from
              existing ones.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Governance permanence.</strong> The Council (Wyoming DUNA)
              governs the protocol; the operating company licenses IP and runs
              optional frontends. No single entity's failure ends the network —
              and no competitor structured as a single issuer can copy that
              without ceasing to be itself.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </section>

        <!-- 10 · RISKS -->
        <section id="risks" class="memo-section" data-memo-section>
          <h2 class="display display--md">VIII. Risks, Stated Plainly</h2>
          <div class="memo-table-wrap">
            <table class="memo-table memo-table--risks">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="col">Risk</th>
                  <th scope="col">Mitigation</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">Vault adoption is slower than planned</th>
                  <td>The Bear case models exactly this — 18 vaults by Year 5, not 40 — and still returns ~2.9x. CAC payback under two months means each signed vault is almost immediately accretive.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">Regulatory reclassification</th>
                  <td>The architecture was designed backwards from the risk register: the vault holds title, OpCo holds nothing, instruments are engineered against securities and stablecoin characterization, and Paul Hastings is on record. The GENIUS Act and March 2026 SEC/CFTC guidance moved the rails toward us.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">Gold price stalls</th>
                  <td>The flat-gold toggle shows the business grows without price help, and the Bear case assumes gold reaching only $6,500 by Year 5. A stalling gold price reduces TVL marks, but the fee engine runs on actions — mints, transfers, trades — and treasury drawdown capacity remains.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">Incumbent response (Paxos / Tether / LBMA)</th>
                  <td>Single issuers cannot become neutral multi-vault standards without abandoning their model; the hubs are charter-bound to their regions. The realistic incumbent response is to join the standard.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">Series A doesn't close on time</th>
                  <td>Modeled: the Bear case closes the A at month 22 with the treasury auto-bridging, minimum cash stays positive, and the company reaches profitability regardless.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">Key person</th>
                  <td>Two technical founders plus a CTO; Guardian multi-sig removes single-actor control of infrastructure; the Council survives the company.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">Smart-contract failure</th>
                  <td>Two audits in Year 1, pre-launch audits for every subsequent module, and monthly third-party proof-of-reserve attestation per vault.</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 11 · TEAM & GOVERNANCE -->
        <section id="team" class="memo-section" data-memo-section>
          <h2 class="display display--md">IX. Team &amp; Governance</h2>
          <ul class="memo-list">
            <li>
              <strong>Cole [●] — Co-founder.</strong> [1–2 sentence bio:
